{"id":"kancamagus-scenic-byway","generatedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z","designation":"National Scenic Byway","parkCode":null,"source":{"roadArticle":"New Hampshire Route 112","revisionId":1357276803,"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Hampshire_Route_112"},"attribution":{"license":"CC BY-SA 4.0","licenseUrl":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","articleUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Hampshire_Route_112","text":"Route, junction, and history details adapted from the Wikipedia article \"New Hampshire Route 112\", by Wikipedia contributors, licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0."},"sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia","src":"wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Hampshire_Route_112","revisionId":1357276803,"retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"},{"name":"Federal Highway Administration — National Scenic Byways","src":"fhwa","url":"https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways","retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"},{"name":"OpenStreetMap contributors (ODbL)","src":"osm","url":"https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright","retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"}],"endpoints":{"from":"Bath, NH","to":"Conway, NH","via":["Easton, NH","Woodstock, NH"]},"itinerary":[{"seq":1,"place":"Bath","state":"NH","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":0,"toNextMi":8.7,"note":"The drive begins here","control":["Woodsville","Bath","Lisbon"],"lat":44.03026,"lng":-71.6865,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":2,"place":"Easton","state":"NH","kind":"town","mileFromStart":8.7,"toNextMi":9.2,"note":"Junction toward Benton","control":["Benton","Easton","Franconia"],"lat":44.04678,"lng":-71.66557,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":3,"place":"Woodstock","state":"NH","kind":"town","mileFromStart":17.9,"toNextMi":38.5,"note":"Junction toward Warren","control":["Warren","North Lincoln","Thornton","Plymouth","Concord","Franconia Notch","Littleton"],"lat":44.03026,"lng":-71.6865,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":4,"place":"Conway","state":"NH","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":56.4,"toNextMi":null,"note":"The drive ends here","control":["Conway","Ossipee","Rochester"],"lat":43.97825,"lng":-71.13345,"src":"wikipedia"}],"history":{"paragraphs":["The Kancamagus Highway opened in August 1959, after two dead-end stretches of road were linked, creating a connection between US 3 in Lincoln and NH 16 in Conway. Locally known as \"The Kanc\" or \"The Kank\", the road was paved in 1964, and in the winter of 1966–67 it was plowed for the first time.","The highway is named after Kancamagus (pronounced \"cain-kah-MAW-gus\", \"Fearless One\"), third and final sagamore of the Penacook Confederacy of Native American tribes. Nephew of Wonalancet and grandson of Passaconaway, Kancamagus ruled what is now southern New Hampshire. After English settlers arrested a number of Pennacook tribe members, he was forced to make the decision in 1691 to move north into upper New Hampshire and what is now Quebec, Canada.","On February 9, 2004, University of Massachusetts Amherst student Maura Murray crashed her car on Route 112 near Woodsville. She disappeared shortly after this incident and her fate remains unknown.","Following Hurricane Irene in August 2011, two sections of NH 112 were closed, pending repair work and evaluation of damage. The Kancamagus Highway was closed from the Sabbaday Falls picnic area across Kancamagus Pass to the Discovery Trail parking area in the eastern part of Lincoln. A section of the western portion of NH 112 along the Wild Ammonoosuc River was closed; as of September 6, 2011, a single lane of the western section had been reopened. By late June 2012, the highway was completely reopened, though some stretches were still being repaved."],"sourceSection":"History","src":"wikipedia"},"highlights":[{"n":"Bath","d":"The drive begins here","q":"Bath","lat":44.16416667,"lng":-71.96611111,"src":"wikipedia"},{"n":"Conway","d":"The drive ends here","q":"Conway","lat":44.00861111,"lng":-71.07166667,"src":"wikipedia"}],"references":[{"n":1,"text":"Bureau of Planning & Community Assistance (February 20, 2015). \"NH Public Roads\". Concord, New Hampshire: New Hampshire Department of Transportation. Retrieved April 7, 2015.","url":"http://www.granit.unh.edu/data/search?dset=roads_dot"},{"n":2,"text":"\"Kancamagus Scenic Byway\". America's Byways. Federal Highway Administration. Archived from the original on March 6, 2014. Retrieved March 23, 2015.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20140306141740/http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways/byways/2458"},{"n":3,"text":"Kancamagus Highway Closures","url":"http://www.kancamagushighway.com/closures.htm"},{"n":4,"text":"Town of Woodstock official website: Interactive Mapping","url":"http://www.caigisonline.com/woodstocknh/"},{"n":5,"text":"\"It Climbs the Mountains In Lincoln-Woodstock Area\". The Boston Globe. September 13, 1959. p. 16-A. Retrieved February 8, 2019 – via newspapers.com.","url":"https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28188215/it_climbs_the_mountains_in/"},{"n":6,"text":"\"Kancamagus Scenic Byway\". Kancamagus Highway.com. Retrieved June 1, 2026.","url":"https://kancamagushighway.com/"},{"n":7,"text":"\"Editor's Choice: Kancamagus Highway - North Conway & North Woodstock, NH\". Visit New Hampshire. Retrieved May 29, 2026.","url":"https://www.visit-newhampshire.com/state/editors-choice-nconway-kancamagushwy-nwoodstock/"},{"n":8,"text":"Erickson, J. O'Brien (July 5, 1964). \"Take Plenty of Film For This Shunpike Trip\". The Boston Globe. p. 43. Retrieved February 8, 2019 – via newspapers.com.","url":"https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28188856/take_plenty_of_film_for_this_shunpike/"}],"routeLine":[[44.03026,-71.6865],[44.03,-71.6856],[44.02997,-71.68479],[44.0301,-71.68399],[44.03034,-71.68322],[44.03077,-71.68242],[44.03694,-71.67671],[44.03636,-71.6771],[44.03553,-71.67781],[44.03498,-71.67833],[44.03236,-71.68078],[44.0314,-71.68168],[44.03235,-71.68092],[44.03322,-71.68013],[44.03398,-71.6794],[44.03455,-71.67887],[44.0358,-71.67774],[44.03641,-71.67722],[44.03694,-71.67671],[44.03743,-71.67627],[44.03792,-71.67574],[